d placed in an American POW camp. He was eventually released and then immigrated to Canada where he became John. The Constructed Mennonite is a unique account of a life shaped by Stalinism, Nazism, migration, famine, and war. It investigates the tenuous spaces where individual experiences inform and become public history; it studies the ways in which memory shapes identity, and reveals how context and audience shape autobiographical narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aGermany.  aManitoba.  aMennonite.  aRussia.  aSecond World War.  aWWI.  aWorld War II.  ahistory.  aimmigration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755436040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554360423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554360/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles